03874nam a22006735i 9780814739815DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19981998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147398157 a10.18574/97808147398152doi  a(DE-B1597)548551  a(OCoLC)782877967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ1420b.S68 1998 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a305.4/0973/09042211 aSpurlock, John C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew and Improved :bThe Transformation of American Women's Emotional Culture /cJohn C. Spurlock, Cynthia Magistro. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory of Emotions ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Self and Emotion in the Early Twentieth Century -- t2. Flaming Youth -- t3. The Single Woman -- t4. The Flapper Wife -- t5. The Silver Cord -- t6. The Fountain -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the Victorian era drew to a close, American culture experienced a vast transformation. In many ways, the culture changed even more rapidly and profoundly for women. The "new woman," the "new freedom," and the "sexual revolution" all referred to women moving out of the Victorian home and into the public realm that men had long claimed as their own. Modern middle-class women made a distinction between emotional styles that they considered Victorian and those they considered modern. They expected fulfillment in marriage, companionship, and career, and actively sought up-to-date versions of love and happiness, relieved that they lived in an age free from taboo and prudery. Drawing on the diaries, letters, and memoirs of women from a wide range of backgrounds and geographic regions, this volume offers insights into middle-class women's experiences of American culture in this age of transition. It documents the ways in which that culture--including new technologies, advertising, and movies--shaped women's emotional lives and how these women appropriated the new messages and ideals. In addition, the authors describe the difficulties that women encountered when emotional experiences failed to match cultural expectations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEmotions in literature. 0aEmotionsxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxPsychologyxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aMagistro, Cynthia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814739815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814739815.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK